figureCitation.captionText-1: FIGURE 15. Distribution map of Coprophanaeus terrali, C. dardanus and C. telamon in northern Mato Grosso, Brazil. Note that C. telamon is limited to west Juruena and north of lower Teles Pires Rivers (however passing Juruena much farther south), C. dardanus east of Xingu River (also in western varzea), and C. terrali in higher lands between these three rivers.

subSubSection.paragraph:
Comments. We have observed some characteristics in
C. dardanus
that differ from those cited by Edmonds & Zidek ( 2010 ). The pronotum of this species, as well as that of
C. terrali
, possesses a distinct midlongitudinal sulcus, contrary to Edmonds & Zidek’s observation that this sulcus was absent. The cap of the anterior metasternal angle is variable: although it is simple in many specimens, as stated by Edmonds & Zidek, many others have it strongly forked. In addition, the cap is often followed by a small fossa (such as cited by Edmonds & Zidek for
C. degallieri
and
C. parvulus
), and the metasternal disk has a weak midlongitudinal sulcus. These new observations are incorporated in our modification of Edmonds & Zidek’s key above.
